<subSubSection id="68C7E60B2AA94459597F2ED276A2CD63" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="61D5CF0650C3655A58A2BB4C95DC1DAB" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Discussion.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="BBEE69A67DCE8455E0DD1BDF2154F42B" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">
<taxonomicName id="40EF5873BA33C39F44DF98C31182FC43" authorityName="Ohe &amp; Araki" authorityYear="1973" class="Actinopterygii" family="Myctophidae" genus="Diaphus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Diaphus hataii" order="Myctophiformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="hataii">
<emphasis id="BA035DA0C9E32AEE59111EE2A5A0C8E9" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Diaphus hataii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is by far the most common myctophid otolith-based species throughout the early and early middle Miocene (late Burdigalian and early Langhian) of Japan, and it represents about 73% of all myctophid otoliths studied here. It is characterized by a short rostrum, which is not or only a fraction longer than the antirostrum; a convex inner face; a ratio OL:OH of 1.20-1.35 (adjusted from 
<bibRefCitation id="8D0F7886A2DF370C06CA924B09BD7E46" author="Schwarzhans, W" journalOrPublisher="Palaeo Ichthyologica" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" pagination="83 - 150" refId="B61" refString="Schwarzhans, W, Aguilera, OA, 2013. Otoliths of the Myctophidae from the Neogene of tropical America. Palaeo Ichthyologica 13: 83 - 150" title="Otoliths of the Myctophidae from the Neogene of tropical America." volume="13" year="2013">Schwarzhans and Aguilera 2013</bibRefCitation>
); a ratio OCL:CCL of 1.7-2.0; an oscillating dorsal rim of the ostium; 8-12 fine denticles along the ventral rim (adjusted from 
<bibRefCitation id="7FD667C05B8166F37417F59315C1D8A0" author="Schwarzhans, W" journalOrPublisher="Palaeo Ichthyologica" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" pagination="83 - 150" refId="B61" refString="Schwarzhans, W, Aguilera, OA, 2013. Otoliths of the Myctophidae from the Neogene of tropical America. Palaeo Ichthyologica 13: 83 - 150" title="Otoliths of the Myctophidae from the Neogene of tropical America." volume="13" year="2013">Schwarzhans and Aguilera 2013</bibRefCitation>
); and a more or less strongly developed predorsal lobe. 
<bibRefCitation id="0A86A4ED3E78DE4276B128ADD9EB1F5B" author="Schwarzhans, W" journalOrPublisher="Palaeo Ichthyologica" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" pagination="83 - 150" refId="B61" refString="Schwarzhans, W, Aguilera, OA, 2013. Otoliths of the Myctophidae from the Neogene of tropical America. Palaeo Ichthyologica 13: 83 - 150" title="Otoliths of the Myctophidae from the Neogene of tropical America." volume="13" year="2013">Schwarzhans and Aguilera (2013)</bibRefCitation>
used the latter character as an important means by which to distinguish 
<taxonomicName id="FFF7BC1D9FB6B02B1CED6C7A5FE81B1E" genus="D." lsidName="D. hataii" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" rank="species" species="hataii">
<emphasis id="F57943F8BF46CFD68CE84F878D057C6B" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">D. hataii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the contemporaneous 
<taxonomicName id="9DD5DF7E1582F070A78C3E020E989610" genus="D." lsidName="D. austriacus" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" rank="species" species="austriacus">
<emphasis id="077D92E18A4A49AE82C4100E59633977" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">D. austriacus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Koken, 1891), but the newly available material shows a certain degree of variability, as most species show such predorsal lobe (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="55B2E46916E6947502BDEE3D54335272" captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="F9" captionText="Figure 9. A-I: Diaphus cassidiformis (Frost, 1933), SMF PO 101.138, Yatsuo, Toyama City, Kurosedani Formation, level K 5; J-AC: Diaphus hataii Ohe &amp; Araki, 1973; J-L: SMF PO 101.139, Mizunami City, Oidawara Formation; M-N, Q-V: SMF PO 101.140, Tsuyama City, Takakura Formation, levels MS 06, MS 07, MS 52, MS 90; O-P: SMF PO 101.141, Fuchu machi, Toyama City, Higashibessho Formation, level H 20; W-AA: SMF PO 101.142, Makino River, Iga City, Makino Formation, level A 1; AB-AC: SMF PO 101.143, Inabacho, Tsu City, Katada Formation, level ML 2305; AD-AG: Diaphus biatlanticus (Weiler, 1959); AD-AF: SMF PO 101.144, Mizunami City, Oidawara Formation; AG: SMF PO 101.145, Tsuyama, Takakura Formation, level h; AH-AJ: Diaphus sp. 2, SMF PO 101.146, Mizunami City, Oidawara Formation." figureDoi="10.3897/zitteliana.96.83571.figure9" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/694123" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">9J, M, O, Q, R</figureCitation>
), while others show a moderately developed predorsal lobe (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="7806985496ABD89D687188BD9B882C6F" captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="F9" captionText="Figure 9. A-I: Diaphus cassidiformis (Frost, 1933), SMF PO 101.138, Yatsuo, Toyama City, Kurosedani Formation, level K 5; J-AC: Diaphus hataii Ohe &amp; Araki, 1973; J-L: SMF PO 101.139, Mizunami City, Oidawara Formation; M-N, Q-V: SMF PO 101.140, Tsuyama City, Takakura Formation, levels MS 06, MS 07, MS 52, MS 90; O-P: SMF PO 101.141, Fuchu machi, Toyama City, Higashibessho Formation, level H 20; W-AA: SMF PO 101.142, Makino River, Iga City, Makino Formation, level A 1; AB-AC: SMF PO 101.143, Inabacho, Tsu City, Katada Formation, level ML 2305; AD-AG: Diaphus biatlanticus (Weiler, 1959); AD-AF: SMF PO 101.144, Mizunami City, Oidawara Formation; AG: SMF PO 101.145, Tsuyama, Takakura Formation, level h; AH-AJ: Diaphus sp. 2, SMF PO 101.146, Mizunami City, Oidawara Formation." figureDoi="10.3897/zitteliana.96.83571.figure9" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/694123" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">9T, V, W</figureCitation>
); there are also specimens with a rather regularly curved dorsal rim (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="355ADA6BF52B3AC0BEB7EB28537FCF69" captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="F9" captionText="Figure 9. A-I: Diaphus cassidiformis (Frost, 1933), SMF PO 101.138, Yatsuo, Toyama City, Kurosedani Formation, level K 5; J-AC: Diaphus hataii Ohe &amp; Araki, 1973; J-L: SMF PO 101.139, Mizunami City, Oidawara Formation; M-N, Q-V: SMF PO 101.140, Tsuyama City, Takakura Formation, levels MS 06, MS 07, MS 52, MS 90; O-P: SMF PO 101.141, Fuchu machi, Toyama City, Higashibessho Formation, level H 20; W-AA: SMF PO 101.142, Makino River, Iga City, Makino Formation, level A 1; AB-AC: SMF PO 101.143, Inabacho, Tsu City, Katada Formation, level ML 2305; AD-AG: Diaphus biatlanticus (Weiler, 1959); AD-AF: SMF PO 101.144, Mizunami City, Oidawara Formation; AG: SMF PO 101.145, Tsuyama, Takakura Formation, level h; AH-AJ: Diaphus sp. 2, SMF PO 101.146, Mizunami City, Oidawara Formation." figureDoi="10.3897/zitteliana.96.83571.figure9" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/694123" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">9Z</figureCitation>
, AA, AB). We could not recognize sufficient consistency or additional characters that would warrant splitting of 
<taxonomicName id="81EE7603818923C540D92A9EE2C42437" genus="D." lsidName="D. hataii" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" rank="species" species="hataii">
<emphasis id="0972A3AB692155C976BE99CF1AB2A015" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">D. hataii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
into separate species. However, this also means that the distinction between 
<taxonomicName id="A1D8C9ED19F93CE26FB731B766C79295" genus="D." lsidName="D. hataii" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" rank="species" species="hataii">
<emphasis id="8214119D4F2758CE241C18C9EBC6F8E9" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">D. hataii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="D0623429D25D39FFAFAFC62553FEFDB5" genus="D." lsidName="D. austriacus" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" rank="species" species="austriacus">
<emphasis id="FD71F210F82B07C8794C83267E2AB47C" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">D. austriacus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
becomes less clear. However, the specimens with a regularly curving dorsal rim are also slightly more elongate than the specimens with a distinct predorsal lobe (OL:OH = 1.25-1.35 vs. 1.20-1.25), while specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="0447C86BFB4A967C92E59BA362DD9078" genus="D." lsidName="D. austriacus" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" rank="species" species="austriacus">
<emphasis id="5EE121DD043F7FD6AFE50553DEBFF7FB" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">D. austriacus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
do not exhibit a predorsal lobe and are more compressed (OL:OH = 1.1-1.2, rarely to 1.25). In addition, 
<taxonomicName id="AB7D290CCCC9442AB667E325603E67DA" genus="D." lsidName="D. hataii" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" rank="species" species="hataii">
<emphasis id="94A334B22A6F8163C12B1855E129CD7B" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">D. hataii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is thinner than 
<taxonomicName id="8BB9B6FE3C64C98EF04647E71A041353" genus="D." lsidName="D. austriacus" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" rank="species" species="austriacus">
<emphasis id="0B18A0BCBF90502292E6769E0931C21E" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">D. austriacus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(OH:OT = 3.5-4.0 vs. 3.0-3.5) and shows more denticles along the ventral rim of the otolith (8-12 vs. 6-8). We maintain the view that two separate species existed during the late early Miocene (Burdigalian) and middle Miocene (chiefly Langhian), with 
<taxonomicName id="67DFA2BBA02FA92192AFDD7AE8C7EE3C" genus="D." lsidName="D. hataii" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" rank="species" species="hataii">
<emphasis id="4501AB5E6A03BC12993CE1DC71343D37" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">D. hataii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
being widely distributed in the tropics and the northern hemisphere from Europe through Central America and Japan, while 
<taxonomicName id="EA855E379ED2919344097EE0567ED22F" genus="D." lsidName="D. austriacus" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" rank="species" species="austriacus">
<emphasis id="18B496E28284D3826D8C39CB2D8D1066" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">D. austriacus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
appears to have been geographically restricted to Europe and the tropical Atlantic. A further potential vicariant species could be 
<taxonomicName id="5565EFD6EC91D70EEC091E96622BA268" genus="D." lsidName="D. curvatus" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" rank="species" species="curvatus">
<emphasis id="125C912BA1F3BE11DA47640AACFCC0C2" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">D. curvatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Schwarzhans, 1980 in the early and middle Miocene of the South Pacific (New Zealand and Chile; see Biostratigraphic Evaluation chapter).
</paragraph>
